metric	concept	intuition	scope	modelType	requiredStructure	formula	limitations	references
node-level homophily	homophily	The degree to which an node is connected to nodes similar to itself.	individual	graph	groups	$$\frac{d_i(v)}{d(v)}$$	- Interpretation can depend heavily on the relative sizes of the groups. (For example $H_i=0.5$ might imply significant polarisation if $A_i$ is small (say, 10% of the population), but would be consistent with no homophily if $A_i$ is 50% of the population.)	[Interian et al. (2022)](https://arxiv.org/abs/2207.13799)
group-level homophily	homophily	The degree to which vertices in a cluster are connected to cluster are connected to vertices in their own cluster.	group	graph	groups	$$\frac{\sum_{v\in A_i}d_i(v)}{\sum_{v\in A_i} d(v)}$$	Interpretation can depend heavily on the relative sizes of the groups. For example $H_i=0.5$ might imply significant polarisation if $A_i$ is small (say, 10% of the population), but would be Consistent with no homophily if $A_i$ is 50% of the population.	[Interian et al. (2022)](https://arxiv.org/abs/2207.13799)
population homophily	homophily	The degree to which all vertices are connected to vertices in their own clusters.	population	graph	groups	$$\frac{\sum_{v\in V} d_{s(v)}(v)}{\sum_{v\in V}d(v)}$$	Interpretation can depend heavily on the relative sizes of the groups. For example $H_i=0.5$ might imply significant polarisation if $A_i$ is small (say, 10% of the population), but would be Consistent with no homophily if $A_i$ is 50% of the population.	[Interian et al. (2022)](https://arxiv.org/abs/2207.13799)
modularity	modularity	The number of intra-group connections relative to the number of inter-group connections.	population	graph	groups	$$Q = \frac{1}{4\|E\|} \sum_{u,v\in V, v\neq u} (a_{uv}-\frac{d(u)d(v)}{e\|E\|}) \cdot g(u,v)$$		[Interian et al. (2022)](https://arxiv.org/abs/2207.13799)
E-I index	modularity	The number of intra-group connections relative to the number of inter-group connections.	population	graph	groups	$$\frac{ET-IT}{ET+IT}.$$		[Interian et al. (2022)](https://arxiv.org/abs/2207.13799)
random walk controversy	controversy	The likelihood of crossing between groups when randomly traversing the graph.	population	graph	groups	$$RWC = \mathbb{P}(A) - \mathbb{P}(B)$$	Some argue that it is not capable of detecting controversy using only structural data. Propose a "biased random walk" that also incorporates content information.	[Interian et al. (2022)](https://arxiv.org/abs/2207.13799)
node-level random walk controversy	controversy	The likelihood of crossing between groups when randomly traversing the graph.	individual	graph	groups	$$RWC(v,X) = \frac{ \mathbb{P}(\textsf{start}=v\mid\textsf{end}=X^+) }{ \mathbb{P}(\textsf{start}=v\mid\textsf{end}=X^+) + \mathbb{P}(\textsf{start}=v\mid\textsf{end}=Y^+) }$$	Some argue that it is not capable of detecting controversy using only structural data. Propose a "biased random walk" that also incorporates content information.	[Interian et al. (2022)](https://arxiv.org/abs/2207.13799)
degree of balance	balance	Consistency with propoerties such as "my friend's friend is my friend" and "my friend's enemy is my enemy".	population	graph		$$\beta(G) = \frac{ c^+(G) }{ c(G) }$$		[Interian et al. (2022)](https://arxiv.org/abs/2207.13799)
